[much of Mary Kuhner's letter para-phrased to save space]

[ general trends for weather (with deserts and forests being examples) ]

Mountains, when coupled with winds can create some interesting weather
patterns.  The leeward side of the mountain range will tend to be drier
than the windward side.  Very high mountain ranges can border your
deserts very nicely.  The windward side, being rained on quite frequently,
can either become a jungle (tropical rain forest), a deciduous (sp?) forest
(temperate weather), a coniferous forest (temperate to arctic), or a snowy
waste (arctic).

Also note that deserts may be found on the coast.  If you postulate that
the level of the seas on your planet have dropped very slowly, great
deposits of salt can be left along the coast.  Such salt deposits tend
to ruin the land for life (although some animals might venture there
occasionally to supplement the salt in their diet).  Plant life will be
very scarce, and will tend toward those forms that are carnivorous
(giant honeydews, venus fly traps, et al).

[ possible expectations for population density ]

Hunter-gatherers will tend to take up very large ranges.  Villages of
not more than a score of people will tend to be the norm, with each village
being one family unit.  Families will tend to be greatly extended, with all
males of a child's father's generation being called father.  Polygynany will
tend to also be the norm, with females being sold, traded, or given, to
other males to extend the family.

Agricultural societies will tend to be more numerous, although primitive
agriculturalists will not be too much more numerous than hunter-gatherers.
Big-men will begin to appear as rulers.  Big-men are more middle men for
moving goods around than true rulers, but they do hold some power.  The
primary crops will be on the order of yams, and other quickly perishable
foods.

As agriculture progresses, the big-men will be replaced by chiefs.  Chiefs
will act as store-houses of grain (grain being more rot resistant than
yams).  The chiefs will also act as war leaders, although they may have to
bow at times to the wishes of the tribal medicine man.

[ when will nations begin to appear ]

Nations begin to form when the use of land becomes a priviledge rather than
a right.  A chief might become so powerful that he can order his people to
leave certain portions of land to him, or to work those lands purely for his
own gain.  At such a time, the chief will have become a ruler of a nation.
An army will very likely follow, so as to be able to protect the chief's 
properties.  These armies will be paid from the store that the chief has
accumulated, or is accumulating.

City-states should be the first step to forming a nation, with larger nations
developing as the rulers of city-states expand their influence by might of arms.
The ruler of each city-state will be very proud of his/her accomplishment, and
will be almost certainly contemptuous of his peers (some craftier rulers will
play the innocent, openly admiring the accomplishment of another while plotting
the overthrow of his "hero").


With magic added in, anything is possible, but civilization will tend to grow
in places where agriculture is dominant, with hunting reduced to a secondary
role.  Frontier lands, and borders where wars are common will tend to revert
to hunting-gathering, or will rely on more secure locations for provisions.

Should an area be found to be rich in a commodity, whether that commodity be
wood, gold, silver, iron, coal, or whatever, somebody will move there to
exploit the abundance.  This does not necessarily mean that great cities will
just suddenly pop up, but the seeds will be planted.  And if you should happen
to have a river or two meet, one from an iron-rich province, and one from
a coal-rich region ...

>Mary Kuhner

		Brian Bowers
		cs2551af@charon.unm.edu


