> Subject: Universe (small scale)
> 
> Suppose that one has people on this landscape.  What are the patterns
> of population density to be expected?

Consider that humans tend to congregate either where easy transport is
available (river mouths, river confluences, either side of a mountain
pass, harbors, road intersections, etc...), or where raw resources are
available (good farm land [low pop density, but you'll have a town for
trading and staples for every X many acres], mines [which leads to ghost
towns too], good fishing [generally from a safe harbor area], etc..)

I know it's not much on numbers, but it'll point you in the general
direction....

> At what size do small local units start aggregating into larger ones?

With agrarian societies, the small farm will be part of a loose agregate
of farms which all center on a town which is no more than 1/4 of a day away
by whatever is the normal mode of transportation.  You need 1/4th of a day
to travel to the town for market, 1/2 of a day for market, and 1/4th to travel
home.  So, the size of your basic 'agregate' depends on the level of
technology available.

If your only transport for the average joe is his feet, then the largest
'basic agregate' will be no more than 6 miles radius.  Give him a horse,
and you get maybe 12 miles.  A team with wagon, you get maybe 20 miles,
more if it's possible to 'lay-over' at the destination.  A car with good
roads? Maybe 100 miles radius.

Larger agregates depend heavily on terain.  A flat plain surrounded by
mountains will probably be under one 'overlord'.  (Call him whatever you
want, he's the leader...)  Mountainous terrain will probably have more,
smaller, units centered on valleys. etc....  Eventually, you reach the
continent size.  The largest independent unit again depends on technology.

If the best you have is feet.  The largest 'nation' will probably be no
more than 100 miles radius, and basically linked by a common language.
If you have modern tech, then you can probably cover a continent.

> I have "nations" in my campaign world where loose aggregates of city-states
> might be more reasonable, given low population densities.
> 
> I'm not interested in simulating history as such.  For me, all the interest
> and use in history lies in the unique, unexpected human quirks.  Mass
> trends predicatable by psychohistory are background at best.

I think I would recommend the PBS series "The Day the Universe Changed".
It should give you a good feeling for how individual human quirks can have
a profound impact on the course of humanity at large.

> Mary Kuhner

