Well, here's what I've learned or have been able to figure out from just
camping out:
	1)	Clouds tend to form over bodies of water and large
	concentrations of vegetation.
	2)	Winds tend to blow from oceans to the land during the
	day, and from land to the oceans at night (I do know the
	scientific reason for this if anyone wants it).
	3)	High mountains tend to cause clouds to pile up against
	them, letting them all over as one big, dense cloud, instead of
	the scattered clouds they would have been.  When they get on the
	other side of the mountains, they tend to drop their load of rain,
	causing flooding (if enough clouds piled up).
	4)	Deserts expand over time.  The expansion progresses in
	all directions, but quickest in the direction that the wind in
	that area is most likely to blow.
	5)	Over a particular piece of land, there will usually be
	two layers of wind, each blowing in different directions.  The upper
	layer will always be faster.  On Earth, the lower layer of wind
	spirals clockwise out of high pressure zones, and counter-clockwise
	into low pressure zones in the Northern hemisphere, and vice versa
	in the Southern hemisphere (I may have this backwards).  The air
	flowing into low pressure zones travels higher, cooling and forming
	clouds, and then away from the low pressure zone, forming the upper
	layer of wind.  In High pressure zones, the wind leaving is actually
	wind from the upper layer which has  descended and reversed course.
	6)	Valleys can trap, redirect, and strengthen winds that blow
	up their lengths.  One example of this is the infamous Santa Ana
	winds of Southern California autumns.  Around mid-September, winds
	in Mexico blow northward over the deserts East of San Diego, and 
	around Palm Springs, warming up as they go.  The then travel 
	through the Imperial Valley (?) which funnels the wind into the
	LA basin.  Viola!  Hot, fast winds...   This can happen anywhere
	you have the geography for it.

Well.   That's about it...

							Darren


