Subject: Re: Map-making techniques
Message-ID: <5286@csli.STANFORD.EDU>
Date: 26 Aug 88 19:35:12 GMT
References: <1125@agora.UUCP< <1798@imagen.UUCP< <9927@dartvax.Dartmouth.EDU>
Reply-To: institut@csli.UUCP (LSA Summer Institute Account)
Organization: Center for the Study of Language and Information, Stanford U.
Lines: 29

This is not a flame of the technique.
Rather, it is an opinion, mixed with a bit of advice for beginning DM's.

You don't _really_ need to watch a computer spin the globe a few times
to come up with a viable map.  Simply sketch out what *you* want to see
on the map; it doesn't have to in scale or that accurate, if you don't
want it to.  In-scale maps are only really good for long-distance travel,
and you can just guesstimate these times, anyway.

I prefer my method of taking an existing USGS map and sinking it.  Very
realistic, easily something plate tectonics could come up with (after all,
it did).  Most players won't realize what's going on, especially with the
abysmal knowledge of geography most people have today.

If you _do_ add something, and a player says "that doesn't make sense!", you
can always say "the dwarves did it" or "well, that's what happens when a
mage creates a volcano", or something.

All that you really need to worry about is weather.  The absolute best
preparation for this is a basic course in geography, but if necessary,
you can plug your world into a computer program.  Random charts are
OK, _if_ they make sense; don't have a blizzard one day and a heat wave
the next.


